<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Evidence to the Culture, Media and Sport Committee Inquiry on women/sport</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Christine Ann Wellington [WAS0024]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The benefits of regularly participating in sport are known and unequivocal. Heath benefits are both physical (eg cardio-vascular endurance, co-ordination, flexibility, weight management) and psychological (enjoyment, anti-depressant, self-esteem). Transferable skills - time management, organisation, goal setting, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">teamwork</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> – are also of considerable value. Sport builds bridges and unites communities. Increasing participation is an investment in the overall economic, cultural and social health of our nation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Equity is expected by the public and enshrined in law. It is therefore entirely reasonable to suggest that similar opportunities should exist for women to participate in, succeed at and make a living from sport as they do for men. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">It must be remembered that ‘women/girls’ is not a homogenous category and consideration must be given to differences in income level, age, ethnicity, place of residence and disability.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">This submission considers the barriers to participation, and makes recommendations for overcoming them, at the grassroots and elite level.  Action requires genuine, transparent and honest collaboration between all stakeholders</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Grassroots Level: Barriers and Recommendations for Action</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Barriers to participation at the grassroots can be grouped into: financial, practical, personal/psychological and institutional.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Overcoming barriers and stimulating participation requires an understanding of the varied motivational drivers/triggers: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the factors that influence </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">if</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">why,</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">when</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> females commence and maintain their participation.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> This is captured by the 5’Fs: 1) fun and feel-good factor, 2) fitness, 3) friendship, 4) fundraising and 5) the fight (competition). Taking the barriers and triggers into consideration, below are suggestions for increasing participation at the grassroots level. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Practical barriers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 15pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">These include: limited leisure time (due to work patterns/hours, domestic work, care of child/relatives); lack of access to transport; safety concerns; lack of (access to) quality sports facilities and opportunities; lack of (affordable) childcare facilities; season/climate.  Specific suggestions are as follows:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Improve provision of indoor and outdoor facilities in urban and rural areas. For example, r</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ecreation grounds, school/university playing fields and sports halls, swimming pools, leisure centres, village halls, public pitches/tracks, National Parks and open spaces. Facilitate sharing of facilities, such as opening school sports fields to non-school based clubs.  Increase access to public land and water on a permanent basis, as well as on an informal temporary basis, for sports such as cross country running, orienteering, climbing, canoeing and so forth. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Improve availability of information about existing facilities and clubs using a various media channels (including social media). Give discounts to those organisations that are marketing sports provision and access to physical activity. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ensure clubs and sports facilities are ‘family friendly’: provide affordable crèche facilities or (simultaneous) classes for toddlers and children, offer classes that parents can take part in with their children; facilitate ‘child-minding’ exchanges amongst club/gym members</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Reduce the bureaucracy and time involved in registering for clubs/sports facilities: Sport must move quickly to embrace new technology for example through on-line booking systems or smart leisure cards. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Establish partnerships with transport providers, develop share-a-ride systems, improve facilities such as </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">cycle lanes and footpaths and offer (discounted) public transport to events and sports facilities. P</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">romote locally based physical activity that doesn’t require motorised transport to access: linked to this is the development/maintenance of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">a strategic network of trails for walking, cycling, and horse riding. The Netherlands provides a great example of a comprehensive and safe cycle based infrastructure. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ensure locations or facilities are safe and appropriate for all, especially women and girls: focus also on neighbourhood aesthetics and encourage buddying schemes.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ensure the equitable access of women/girls in allocation of facilities and pitch time.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Offer shorter classes and games, such as 30min spin classes, where benefits can be gained in a short space of time. Enable women to combine activities such as sport and shopping (eg retail outlets that also provide yoga classes) and promote home-based </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">exercise  -</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> dvds, music/motivational cds.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Encourage employers to provide work-based facilities, such as gyms, changing, showers and safe cycle parking. Companies could collaborate to create and share facilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Provide advice and support to young women during key transitions where levels of participation may be affected e.g. during transition from school to employment, after childbirth. Include physical activity and healthy living issues in pre- and post-natal education. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Expand projects to facilitate mobile provision of equipment in rural areas, such as schemes to transport sports equipment from village to village, or ‘mobile gyms’ that can visit schools and colleges on a regular basis. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Sports companies could do more to develop and market products that are suitable for all shapes and sizes, and ethnic backgrounds (eg BME women).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt; widows:0"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Financial barriers:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">These include: limited disposable income; rising/high entry fees; long-term membership requirements for gyms and leisure centres; cost of clothing and equipment. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">If we are to increase participation consideration must be given to a) the actual costs of participation and b) the way we market the sport and our products.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Suggested actions include:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Gyms/clubs: offer free introductions/inductions.  Provide flexibility in the length of sign-up periods with opportunities to trial and observe (‘try before you buy’ schemes) and offer a variety of payment options: monthly direct debits rather than annual subscriptions, or ‘pay as you play’, and recognise and support a variety of family </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">structures/compositions in their membership packages. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Offer vouchers/discounts for other products with membership packages.  The government could subsidise entry to sports facilities – especially for children (replicating the subsidies currently provided for museums and art galleries).  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Sports companies</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">could develop and market more affordable/cheaper ranges, as well as the high end products. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Relaxed dress codes reduce the need to purchase new clothes and equipment. Clubs, gyms, NGOs and companies could offer (and market) opportunities to borrow, exchange or hire equipment, or buy second-hand. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Employers could incentivise employees to participate in physical activity, or contribute to the CSR agenda through volunteering at events or for clubs – incentives can include tax breaks for sports equipment purchases, bike to work schemes, days off in lieu, monetary bonuses or rewards. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Personal/psychological-social</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Personal/psychological-social </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">barriers include: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">lack of confidence and low self esteem/perceptions of ability/body image; perceptions of sport as male-dominated, unfeminine activity; peer pressure; lack of parental support; cultural restrictions; lack of positive role models; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">competitive/aggressive/intimidating environments; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">lack of friends/people to participate with. Suggested actions include: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Consult consumers on what activities should be undertaken, when, where and how.  Schools/colleges and clubs should increase variety and choice in activities - competitive and non-competitive sports, formal and informal environments. Offer rewards for non-position/time based achievement, such as rewarding leadership, improvement, and teamwork skills. ‘Us Girls’ provides a great case study of an organisation offering a range of activities that appeal to all women/girls.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Establish acceptable grouping and class composition, including providing the option of single-sex activities and events, staffed by women.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Relax dress codes, especially with regards BME women and girls.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Encourage companies to produce and market a wider range of products, including for those who are of all sizes and ethnic groups. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Implement advertising and promotional campaigns to improve the image of sport – emphasizing enjoyment and participation for all. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">If sports are seen as exclusive, old-fashioned and chauvinistic, it reduces the likelihood of uptake. A</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> variety of brand ambassadors should be used to celebrate and promote equality and diversity. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Ensure links are made in education and marketing to wider skill development and benefits gained through physical activity. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Combining sport with other activities and interests can help change the perception of sport as an untrendy/unsocial activity, for example some well known sports retailers offer yoga classes/running clubs within their retail outlets. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Increase – and promote - formal and informal buddying/mentoring (‘pay it forward’) programmes, in clubs, workplaces, at leisure centres and also online to help overcome fear and intimidation and provide support and encouragement. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Offer beginner classes that are open to all, perhaps involving existing friendship groups, to reduce feelings of embarrassment and intimidation, and emphasise the fun/friendship/social sides of sport. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ensure privacy, safety and cleanliness in changing rooms and in facilities. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Promote interaction with elite athletes (such as ‘Champions in Schools’ and Youth Sport Trust’s programmes) to inspire, motivate and educate – in schools, colleges, public forums and workplaces. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">At school, ensure that pupils who are unable to take part (due to illness/injury) help with the organisation of PE lessons, hence facilitating skill development and involvement. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Institutional factors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Institutional barriers include: lack of women in leadership positions such as coaching, management roles at all levels; perception of clubs as cliquey and unwelcoming to new members; lack of ongoing training for teachers in provision of good quality PE at school; lack of equity between sexes of athletes competing in major games, events and races. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Ensure gender equality in the numbers of elite athletes participating in major games</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> and ensure equality and diversity in recruitment in organisations at all levels (making the strong commercial and productivity case for gender balance in employment, rather than simply a moral justification). Ensure staff and volunteers are trained in diversity issues, especially the need for gender equality,</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Employers could incentivize employees to do sport. For example through work sports leagues, events and training, as well as the provision of facilities. Employers could match donations for employee’s participation in charity sporting events. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Provide, and fund, on-going </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">capacity building and skill development for all staff and volunteers (including ongoing CPD for PE teachers).  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">In addition to offering a range of competitive and non competitive sports and opportunities for consultation, healthy living/active lifestyles should be mainstreamed into all areas of the national curriculum and in sports provision - the TITLE XI legislation in USA should be examined in detail</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women and Leadership programs (eg professional development workshops designed for women by women) can provide an opportunity for women working/volunteering in the sport to share experiences and ideas.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Clubs should be inclusive and open to new members: giving taster days, providing mentors, and using appropriate marketing (using new communication channels helps</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> to demonstrate a dynamic, modern, and open organisation).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Case study: </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">parkrun organises free, weekly 5km run events in over 200 locations throughout the UK. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">parkrun</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> is also setting up a 2km junior series for 4-14 year olds. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Females currently account for </span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">49.5% of registrations</span><span style="color:#262626; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. The reasons for this equality lie in parkrun’s model which helps to overcome some barriers to participation. parkruns are: simple to organise; </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">free to the user; there is no need to pre-book or be selected; they are organised by the community for the community; events are held in the open air in natural surroundings; they take place regularly (weekly); they are local and easy to access; they are open to all, inclusive and friendly; there is no dress code; they encourage family involvement; they are timed (offering the opportunity to track progress) and events also organise post-run social gatherings. </span><a href="http://www.parkrun.org.uk"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">www.parkrun.org.uk</span></a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Elite level sport</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Elite level sport fosters national pride, provides sporting role models, provides entertainment, </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">creates</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> ‘trickle down’ economic benefits as well as helping to promote grassroots participation</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> However, relative to men, women’s sport is overlooked, under-valued and under-capitalised. It is characterised by: fewer race/competition opportunities; lack of media coverage (especially television) and sport/athlete exposure; insufficient commercial investment in (and financial insecurity of) teams, athletes and events; lack of financial support, and proper employment contracts; lack of women in other roles (such as coaches, high level management/governance and sports agents). Some sports, such as cycling are also characterised by: smaller prize purses (compared to men) and discriminatory rules regarding race and stage distances.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">All of the above factors are interdependent in a vicious circle that perpetuates the undesirable status quo. As a result of the unsupportive framework, female athletes are unable to fulfil their potential. This creates a lack of strength in depth in the female professional ranks in some sports, leading to the misconception that women’s sport is inferior, and is used to justify further inaction. There is a huge and valuable opportunity for all stakeholders to benefit from the full potential of women’s elite sport, with the goal of developing it equitably and sustainably at all levels. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Commercial investment:</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Rights holders (eg governing bodies) must make strong business cases to encourage commercial investment in the women’s sports. Commercial value exists in the relatively ‘uncluttered’ market of women’s sports, especially those with a developed grassroots structure and club network (which provides further market exposure for the sponsor). Women’s sport offers sponsors a unique dual differentiation: distinctive commercial marketing - appealing to both male and female consumers and brands - as well as the CSR benefits of investing in a developing sport with important social benefits. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Women’s sport has an array of inspirational brand ambassadors to promote their sport and commercial partners.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Events/races:</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Event organisers should explore the feasibility of organising more women’s events. Consideration should be given to scheduling of women/men’s events to ensure equality in media coverage. Having women’s races/events alongside men’s events (eg tennis Grand Slams) can help showcase women’s sport to the world; provide a huge boost in publicity and visibility; provide a model for success that can be replicated by other event organisers and kick-start wider reform. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">, in cycling </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">the UCI could use the race licensing system to encourage all World Tour events to hold a women's race. Race owners </span><span style="color:#1a1a1a; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">could also consider increasing prize purses for female athletes (parity with men), to enable them to better make a living. Other support include: payment of </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">appearance fees in exchange for the athlete’s participation in community events/activities, providing transfers and accommodation and marketing athletes in pre event publicity and at the event itself. Race organisers should also consider putting on unique events that are media/spectator friendly, eg the 20-20 cricket series or mixed triathlon relays, supported by the use of </span><span style="color:#1a1a1a; font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">live athlete cams, GPS info and stats analysis, good commentating, attractive branding and so forth. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Governing Bodies:</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> Discriminatory rules that govern some sports should be evaluated and potentially abolished, for example in cycling rules restricting length and duration of races are based on tradition and assumptions that are not substantiated by evidence from respected sports </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">physiologists. NGBs (and teams) should offer holistic support to female athletes, in order that they can maximize their performance: including access to healthcare, nutritionists, psychologists, facilities and technological support. Athletes should be provided with on-going advice and support, from federations especially, to enable them to make a smooth transition (practically and psychologically) to another career, upon retirement. Elite athletes may require PR training in order that they can best represent their sponsors and their chosen sport. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Sports agents:</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> The importance of capable sports managers/agents in negotiating commercial contracts, and facilitating effective athlete marketing, cannot be overemphasised. Federations can help link athletes/teams with respectable managers. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">: Analysis should be undertaken to ascertain whether there is a correlation between investment and success, over various time scales. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Government funding to athletes/teams could be conditional upon participation in grassroots programmes. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">State funding should be channelled, in part, to development athletes to provide them with the seed funding to enable them to train full time, receive the requisite ‘holistic’ support and hence improve so that they can be competitive on the national global stage. Means testing is also important to ensure athletes with lucrative commercial partnerships don’t receive government funding which could be better spent on development athletes</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Others:</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Investment should be made to in ensuring a comprehensive, rigorous and trustworthy national and international anti-doping programme. One that helps to prevent and helps to deter; catches and punishes those that commit offenses and one that educates and informs all involved in sport. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Media coverage </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Sport is sport irrespective of gender. Women’s sport deserves media coverage because it’s an exciting, thrilling, tactical and emotive to watch, not solely because the athletes are female. The Olympics proves this; with 7.6million viewers watching the BBC’s coverage of the women’s Olympic road race for example.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Despite the welcome increase in media coverage of women’s sport over the past year – for example: football, cricket, golf - there is room for improvement. The </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">solution is not as simple as asking for more coverage and expecting the media to act. It is a complex situation that requires that all stakeholders work together to ensure progress.  </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Whilst not exhaustive, the following actions could be taken:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; orphans:0; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">For women’s sport to flourish the focus must be on increasing the quantity and quality of television coverage of events, as well as harmonising this coverage throughout the year and around the world. It takes regular and frequent broadcasts of the same sport to build audience awareness, recognition and interest.  Governing Bodies could acquire the entire broadcasting rights to events and races, with the ability to sell those rights exclusively to one broadcaster for the entire series.  This would increase the commercial appeal of rights to broadcasters and also help to create coherence and consistency in the promotion, packaging and presentation of the sport. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">For example, the WTA recently sold the exclusive media rights to the WTA Tour to BT Sport. It will be important, even if this was not to take </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">place, that</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> the parity is ensured in any media coverage that Federations already own the rights to.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Events must be packaged and presented effectively. </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">This includes both live and highlights programmes, as well as magazine shows to help promote the personalities and brand ambassadors within the sport and a provide more of an aesthetic lifestyle element to the sport’s coverage</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">. Quality commentary and talented, effective interviewers are vital. The increase in female sports presenters, especially in traditionally male dominated sport, should be encouraged. Indeed, greater equality is needed across the board in sports journalism (especially at leadership levels).</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">With the pressure on journalists (especially online) to file copy swiftly, governing bodies, event owners and teams should help facilitate this: encouraging attendance of the media - including </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">providing VIP event access and hospitality, detailed releases, information and readily accessible imagery. Sponsor contracts could incentivise athletes (</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">ag</span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt"> with bonuses) for media coverage. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Social media represents an exceptional commercial opportunity for women’s sport; creating direct relationships with audiences that offer value to sponsors and provide both an alternative channel to traditional media and also a means of influencing and utilising traditional media’s broader reach.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">Local clubs, groups and sports fans should be encouraged to develop relationships with, and feed information to, the local media about women’s sport. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The male-focused sporting trade press should consider greater equality in its editorial and advertising content; covering more female athletes and races and offering information that is appealing to a female audience: helping change perceptions, encourage greater female participation and create female brand ambassadors. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">The mainstream media could be much more proactive in widening their coverage. The stated intention of the Independent newspaper to cover more women’s sport is a good example of this.</span><a name="_GoBack"></a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Including: governmental departments; NGOs; schools, colleges and universities; gyms and leisure centres and other physical activity providers; international and member federations; event organisers; elite athletes and teams, sports brands and commercial sponsors; the media and the public.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">It is worth noting that elite athletes must be embedded in systematic and ongoing local programmes of promotion, mentoring and support involving parents, teachers and significant adults – as well being effectively and appropriately represented in the media - if they are to be effective role models.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Frutiger LT Std 45 Light'; font-size:9pt">Government investment in elite sport should not replace support for activities and programmes that drive participation at the grassroots level, as well as parallel spending on sport through the Departments of Health and Education and Culture, Media and Sport. Of course, the reality is that our elite sport system only prospers when we have a strong talent base on which to draw.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></body></html>